               <desc type="building-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000056c-2 #bibl000056c-3"> As late as 1965, the Fachuan (Dharma
                     Boat) Main Hall stood as a two-story pavilion with a hip-gable roof (<term
                        ref="/keyword/k000143">xieshanding 歇山頂</term>) (Liu and Du 2017, 67). The
                     hall originally spanned five bays in width and four bays in depth. The internal
                     column grid adopted reflected the jinxiang doudi <term ref="/keyword/k000005"
                        >cao</term>（金廂鬥底<term ref="/keyword/k000005">槽</term>) arrangement. The hall
                     was built on a raised platform projecting 40 cm beyond the exterior wall. The
                     front terrace <term ref="/keyword/k000123">(yuetai月臺)</term> remains 12 cm
                     lower than the larger platform, and approximately 50 cm above ground level (Jia
                     2015, 56). The platform structure itself is constructed of brick and stone,
                     with its surface paved with square-cut stone slabs. The central bay of the hall
                     is wider than the secondary bays, and the secondary bays wider than the corner
                     bays. The extended front terrace was likely designed for Buddhist rituals and
                     is believed to have once held an incense burner. In 1966, the entire hall and
                     the statues inside it were destroyed. Today, the only remains are four broken
                     pieces of the original stone pedestal(s). </p>

                  <p source="#bibl000056c-2"> Originally, there was a bronze Buddha triad with a
                     central Buddha framed by two Bodhisattvas on a stone “boat”(chuan 船). Following
                     evidence in the Fozu Tongji 佛祖統紀 and Cefu Yuangui 册府元龜, Liu Youheng and Du Ning
                     suggest at least two Buddhist activities ordered by the <term
                        ref="/keyword/k00082">Tang</term> court were held at this monastery, likely in the Fachuan Main
                     Hall (Liu and Du 2017, 68).</p>

                  <p source="#bibl000056c-2"> The sculpture and stone boat were supported by a
                     Sumeru-style pedestal (Xumizuo 須彌座). The remains of the pedestal are now divided
                     into four sections, which are engraved with lotus petals, cloud patterns, and
                     guardian figures. Scholars believe that the pedestal was repurposed from an
                     earlier stone architectural component. These four segments are the only
                     surviving relics from the Fachuan Main Hall of Kaiyuan Monastery and are
                     currently housed at <placeName ref="/place/000064">Longxing Monastery
                        龍興寺</placeName>. </p>

               </desc>
